{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778092539,"nonce":"KD08KHy32bcLJeb8zWAJCWmMLww=","message":"## Q,R schedule mismatch — C\u0026S sanity test does NOT use C\u0026S's actual Q,R\n\nVerifying the Riccati results against Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott 2019 directly (paper at `~/Main/10 Projects/10 PhD/cs2019.pdf` after the user moved it out of the working tree), I found a discrepancy that needs resolution before we can fully trust the C\u0026S-regime sign.\n\n### What we observed\nProduction Riccati on the C\u0026S regime (k=0.1) gives Δv at 1.5γ* = −0.77% — H∞ very slightly *reduces* peak velocity vs LQR. Both small (\u003c2%), but disagrees on sign with Phase 2 (+1.5%) and (more importantly) appears to disagree with the paper.\n\n### What the paper actually says\nC\u0026S 2019 §'Model' (p. 8139, paragraph following Eq. 15): the robust controller 'displayed higher forward velocity for unperturbed trials' (Fig. 1e). And critically — they explicitly cost-independence-test:\n\n\u003e 'the following predictions were independent of the cost or noise parameters: (1) the robust controller always generated faster movement velocities toward the target.'\n\nSo the paper claims qualitative cost-independence of the velocity-inflation effect on the C\u0026S plant.\n\n### Probable cause: Q,R schedule mismatch, not a Riccati bug\n- **Production uses synthesis_review §2's interpreted Q,R**: mid: Q_pos=I, Q_vel=0; late: Q_pos=4I, Q_vel=0.4I — derived from rlrmp's `running_cost`.\n- **C\u0026S's actual Q (Eq. 15)**: Q_terminal = diag([10⁶, 10⁶, 10⁵, 10⁵, 1, 1]) ramped by α₁(t/N)⁶ — sharp terminal-only ramp.\n\nVery different shapes. So our 'C\u0026S sanity test' is actually testing **rlrmp's Q,R applied to the C\u0026S plant** — neither C\u0026S nor rlrmp faithfully. Not a Riccati bug; the test is testing the wrong thing.\n\n### Uncertainty\n- C\u0026S claims cost-independence but it isn't shown numerically in the paper for *substantially different* Q shapes — they mention an order-of-magnitude sweep (Fig. 1d) but Δv vs Q-shape isn't directly tabulated.\n- If their cost-independence claim holds on rlrmp's Q,R shape too, our −0.77% is a real disagreement and the Riccati needs investigation.\n- If their claim is conditional on a terminal-heavy Q, then velocity inflation depends on Q shape more than the paper claimed — itself an interesting finding for §10 calibration.\n\n### How we'll proceed (immediate)\n1. **Add a faithful C\u0026S Q,R reproduction as a new test** in `tests/test_hinf_riccati.py`: build Q from Eq. 15 on the C\u0026S plant, verify Δv \u003e 0 (matches the paper's qualitative claim).\n2. If faithful Q,R reproduces +Δv but rlrmp Q,R does not on the same plant → document Q-shape sensitivity in synthesis_review §10 (calibration).\n3. If even faithful C\u0026S Q,R fails → bug in the Riccati implementation; investigate.\n\nTracked as a follow-up to `5a44bd3` (no new umbrella child needed; falls under the existing Riccati issue).","files":null}]}